Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that if `z` is a non-reversible move in `x`, then `unreverse z` is not reversible in `unreverse x`.

The key insight is that `unreverse` preserves the game-theoretic equivalence (via `unreverse_equiv`), so if `unreverse z` were reversible in `unreverse x`, we could derive a contradiction using the equivalences.

```lean
/-- `unreverse x` has no reversible positions. -/
theorem not_reversible_unreverse (hy : y ∈ x.unreverse.moves p) : ¬ Reversible x.unreverse y p := by
  rw [moves_unreverse, Set.mem_iUnion₂] at hy
  obtain ⟨y, hy, ⟨z, hz, rfl⟩⟩ := hy
  by_cases h : Reversible x y p
  · sorry
  · rw [reverseSet_of_not_reversible h] at hz
    subst hz
    intro h'
    apply h
    cases p with
    | left =>
      rw [reversible_left] at h' ⊢
      obtain ⟨w, hw, hw'⟩ := h'
      rw [moves_unreverse, Set.mem_iUnion₂] at hw
      obtain ⟨w, hw, ⟨v, hv, rfl⟩⟩ := hw
      have := subposition_of_mem_reverseSet hw hv
      exact ⟨v, reverseSet_of_not_reversible h ▸ hv ▸ hw, 
        (unreverse_equiv v).le.trans (hw'.trans (unreverse_equiv x).ge)⟩
    | right =>
      rw [reversible_right] at h' ⊢
      obtain ⟨w, hw, hw'⟩ := h'
      rw [moves_unreverse, Set.mem_iUnion₂] at hw
      obtain ⟨w, hw, ⟨v, hv, rfl⟩⟩ := hw
      have := subposition_of_mem_reverseSet hw hv
      exact ⟨v, reverseSet_of_not_reversible h ▸ hv ▸ hw,
        (unreverse_equiv x).le.trans (hw'.trans (unreverse_equiv v).ge)⟩
```
